me to sing this song,

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:52.180
and they said that they
wanted me to perform

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:54.830
this song in the film as well.

00:14:54.830 --> 00:14:56.650
There was a very funny
incident, in fact,

00:14:56.650 --> 00:15:00.580
because I still remember that
Rajendra Kumar called me up,

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:04.780
and I had seen him
from my childhood.

00:15:04.780 --> 00:15:07.660
And he had those hit films.

00:15:07.660 --> 00:15:09.150
And I was a big fan of his.

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:14.780
And especially, Rajendra Kumar
had done a lot of musicals.

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:16.990
He had attended
many movies where

00:15:16.990 --> 00:15:19.190
music used to be fantastic.

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:22.130
So I used to love those films.

00:15:22.130 --> 00:15:24.100
So when he called me
up, I was like, really

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:27.800
thrilled to receive his call.

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:30.530
And he probably
hadn't realized--

00:15:30.530 --> 00:15:32.180
so he, just in
that excitement, he

00:15:32.180 --> 00:15:36.950
told me that, Pankaj, you
are acting in my film.

00:15:36.950 --> 00:15:40.230
So I was like,
acting in your film?

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:45.610
So he said-- to me I
didn't want to commit

00:15:45.610 --> 00:15:48.020
right away, because
when he said acting,

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:49.860
I was a little skeptical.

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:52.850
So I said, can I call you
back and let you know?

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:55.220
So he said, OK.

00:15:55.220 --> 00:15:58.970
And then I didn't call
him back because I

00:15:58.970 --> 00:16:01.520
was scared to call him
back because I was not

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:03.170
prepared to be an actor.

00:16:03.170 --> 00:16:06.350
Because with difficulty,
I had made a name

00:16:06.350 --> 00:16:08.970
in the field of singing,
and I said when am I

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:10.970
going to start acting now?

00:16:10.970 --> 00:16:14.240
So I held back.

00:16:14.240 --> 00:16:17.270
So I didn't return his
call for a couple of days.

00:16:17.270 --> 00:16:19.460
He called my eldest
brother Manharji

00:16:19.460 --> 00:16:21.560
because they were very friendly.

00:16:21.560 --> 00:16:23.630
So he called my brother
and told my brother

00:16:23.630 --> 00:16:29.270
that your younger
brother does not

00:16:29.270 --> 00:16:31.871
have any decency, because
he's not returned my call.

00:16:31.871 --> 00:16:32.370
[LAUGHING]

00:16:32.370 --> 00:16:34.130
SPEAKER: You got in trouble.

00:16:34.130 --> 00:16:37.310
PANKAJ UDHAS: And so I got
a call from big brother.

00:16:37.310 --> 00:16:39.020
He says, you should do this.

00:16:39.020 --> 00:16:41.945
You know, because he's such a
senior actor, and how can you--

00:16:41.945 --> 00:16:45.860
so I told him I said, there
is no other reason for me

00:16:45.860 --> 00:16:48.230
not returning his
call, but I said,

00:16:48.230 --> 00:16:56.360
I'm only rather unsure
whether I want to act or not.

00:16:56.360 --> 00:16:58.590
SPEAKER: So this was not
a very common thing that

00:16:58.590 --> 00:16:59.930
used to happen in those times.

00:16:59.930 --> 00:17:00.440
PANKAJ UDHAS: Yes.

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:02.190
SPEAKER: This was the
first time that they

00:17:02.190 --> 00:17:04.920
experimented with this.

00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:07.369
PANKAJ UDHAS: So he told
told me, in that case,

00:17:07.369 --> 00:17:10.450
call him up and tell him
that you don't want to act.

00:17:10.450 --> 00:17:12.290
I said, fair enough.

00:17:12.290 --> 00:17:13.540
I was shaking.

00:17:13.540 --> 00:17:14.869
I called him up.

00:17:14.869 --> 00:17:19.740
And I said, sir, sorry I didn't
return your call, because I

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:22.069
got taken aback
because, I said, I'm not

00:17:22.069 --> 00:17:24.260
prepared to be an actor.

00:17:24.260 --> 00:17:26.210
So he laughed loudly.

00:17:26.210 --> 00:17:27.859
And he said, oh god.

00:17:27.859 --> 00:17:29.660
He said, no, no, no.

00:17:29.660 --> 00:17:32.400
He said, we don't expect
you to be an actor.

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:35.490
But we want you to appear
in the film as Pankaj Udhas,

00:17:35.490 --> 00:17:38.330
and we want you to
appear as yourself

00:17:38.330 --> 00:17:41.900
and sing the song
so that we can say

00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:45.740
that this is Pankaj Udhas
performing in an auditorium.

00:17:45.740 --> 00:17:49.520
And that's how the
song came about.

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:50.840
SPEAKER: It was a huge success.

00:17:50.840 --> 00:17:52.550
That song was like phenomenal.

00:17:52.550 --> 00:17:56.082
It just placed you on
the map of Bollywood.

00:17:56.082 --> 00:17:58.040
And so I want you to come
back to the question.

00:17:58.040 --> 00:18:00.740
You said you tried, and
then you got this fame--

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:02.960
PANKAJ UDHAS: So
just see the fate

00:18:02.960 --> 00:18:08.150
and just see the destiny, that
something where I was probably

00:18:08.150 --> 00:18:12.500
refused, rejected, or
not exactly rejected,

00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:17.380
but I was, I would say,
overlooked probably.

00:18:17.380 --> 00:18:20.480
And suddenly, I find
that all those people

00:18:20.480 --> 00:18:25.710
want to jam with me and
wanted me to work for them.

00:18:25.710 --> 00:18:29.820
So I guess it's at the end of
the day, I think it's destiny.

00:18:29.820 --> 00:18:32.570
SPEAKER: And after "Naam,"
you did many other playbacks.

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:33.060
PANKAJ UDHAS: Oh, yes.

00:18:33.060 --> 00:18:33.410
I did.

00:18:33.410 --> 00:18:34.130
SPEAKER: Many, many.

00:18:34.130 --> 00:18:35.130
PANKAJ UDHAS: Yes, many.

00:18:35.130 --> 00:18:37.070
SPEAKER: But then you
continued this journey

00:18:37.070 --> 00:18:38.870
towards ghazal
singing and towards--

00:18:38.870 --> 00:18:40.640
PANKAJ UDHAS: I always--

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:42.710
my focus was always
ghazal singing,

00:18:42.710 --> 00:18:44.150
and I always wanted to--

00:18:46.850 --> 00:18:48.950
I guess I've reached
a stage in life

00:18:48.950 --> 00:18:53.090
now that, for me,
ghazal singing is not

00:18:53.090 --> 00:18:56.900
just a commercial
venture that I pursue.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:59.150
Or it's not something
which I pursue

00:18:59.150 --> 00:19:01.950
for the sake of money or fame.

00:19:01.950 --> 00:19:03.620
I think I've reached
a point in life

00:19:03.620 --> 00:19:09.750
that I pursue it because I'm
very passionate about it.

00:19:09.750 --> 00:19:12.870
I want to spread it
across the world,

00:19:12.870 --> 00:19:19.400
so that I want a lot of young
talented singers to dig it up.

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:23.440
Because if you want
this particular genre

00:19:23.440 --> 00:19:27.710
to really prosper
and go forward,

00:19:27.710 --> 00:19:33.470
then you need a bunch of young
performers, young singers,

00:19:33.470 --> 00:19:37.527
to come by and take
it up seriously.

00:19:37.527 --> 00:19:38.360
SPEAKER: Yeah, yeah.

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:41.790
PANKAJ UDHAS: And for me, it's
more of a mission now in life

00:19:41.790 --> 00:19:46.470
than just singing
and performing.

00:19:46.470 --> 00:19:51.720
I think I have devoted
nearly 40 years of my life

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:53.630
to this form of music.

00:19:53.630 --> 00:19:56.780
And I don't want that
this form of music

00:19:56.780 --> 00:19:59.380
should suddenly vanish.

00:19:59.380 --> 00:20:00.470
SPEAKER: I agree.

00:20:00.470 --> 00:20:03.530
PANKAJ UDHAS: So I
certainly want that,

00:20:03.530 --> 00:20:05.800
whatever I can contribute.

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:09.230
SPEAKER: So one thing you said
that when you approached Urdu

00:20:09.230 --> 00:20:12.090
teacher, and you said
yourself, [NON-ENGLISH]..

00:20:12.090 --> 00:20:15.430
We just don't see that kind of
dedication in ghazal singers

00:20:15.430 --> 00:20:17.640
today to focus on diction.

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:18.530
What has changed?

00:20:18.530 --> 00:20:22.850
Why is it not that
zeal to do things right

00:20:22.850 --> 00:20:24.890
and to do it perfectly?

00:20:24.890 --> 00:20:27.710
PANKAJ UDHAS: I
guess what I see--

00:20:27.710 --> 00:20:30.020
I'm not talking like an old.

00:20:30.020 --> 00:20:31.380
I don't think I'm that old.

00:20:31.380 --> 00:20:43.140
But what I see today is that the
level of patience has run out.

00:20:43.140 --> 00:20:49.580
And nobody wants to spend years
together to pursue something,

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:51.290
to achieve something.

00:20:51.290 --> 00:20:55.010
I guess there is
a sense, there's

00:20:55.010 --> 00:20:58.770
a feeling, that you want
to do something very fast.

00:20:58.770 --> 00:21:01.970
You want to achieve lots, and
you want to achieve it fast.

00:21:01.970 --> 00:21:07.070
And that's where, I think,
even the artists, that's

00:21:07.070 --> 00:21:12.650
why the singers do not want
to pursue this form of music.

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:17.820
Because I guess
everyone wants a hit.

00:21:17.820 --> 00:21:18.780
Everyone wants that.

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:26.880
You do something, and suddenly,
you become a YouTube sensation.

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:30.050
You have 5 million,
10 million hits.

00:21:30.050 --> 00:21:35.490
And so I think ghazal
singing basically calls

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:38.510
for a very serious approach.

00:21:38.510 --> 00:21:43.830
And it's very
conservative, and it's

00:21:43.830 --> 00:21:46.290
very time-consuming as well.

00:21:46.290 --> 00:21:48.870
So I think you really
need to have patience

00:21:48.870 --> 00:21:54.430
to pursue this form of
music to be successful.

00:21:54.430 --> 00:21:59.670
So, I mean, if any
youngster who wants

00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:03.510
to follow or pursue
this form of music,

00:22:03.510 --> 00:22:07.100
my advice is that you
got to be very patient.

00:22:07.100 --> 00:22:13.770
You got to learn to take
everything in your stride

00:22:13.770 --> 00:22:18.220
in terms of success, or if
you are unsuccessful also,

00:22:18.220 --> 00:22:21.030
because there is no
guarantee that you can

00:22:21.030 --> 00:22:22.927
become an over night sensation.

00:22:22.927 --> 00:22:23.760
SPEAKER: Good, good.

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:26.520
So that's a good message
for [INAUDIBLE],, hopefully

00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:27.384
some of us.

00:22:27.384 --> 00:22:29.050
So you see a lot of
people sitting here.

00:22:29.050 --> 00:22:31.580
There are also people
watching you over live stream,

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:34.500
because we allow people who
cannot come to this campus,

00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:37.560
allow them to be able to
view the chat elsewhere.

00:22:37.560 --> 00:22:38.850
So you brought up YouTube.

00:22:38.850 --> 00:22:41.190
I wanted to ask you
a little bit about,

00:22:41.190 --> 00:22:43.200
what is your thought
of technology

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:44.370
into the world of music?

00:22:44.370 --> 00:22:48.390
We see a lot of your videos, and
ghazals, and albums on YouTube.

00:22:48.390 --> 00:22:51.930
How do you feel that it has
helped the music industry?

00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:58.380
PANKAJ UDHAS: Well, it's a
great, great platform for--

00:22:58.380 --> 00:23:03.600
I would say that for established
singers, it's brilliant.

00:23:03.600 --> 00:23:05.760
But I would say,
even for singers

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:11.880
who are struggling singers who
are trying to make it in life,

00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:14.430
or singers who are--

00:23:14.430 --> 00:23:17.910
YouTube has opened up
a whole new avenue.

00:23:17.910 --> 00:23:20.200
Because let's face it--

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:23.644
I'm talking about the
Indian perspective.

00:23:23.644 --> 00:23:25.810
I'm not talking about the
international perspective.

00:23:25.810 --> 00:23:29.690
But if you look at the
Indian perspective,

00:23:29.690 --> 00:23:33.180
as far as India
is concerned, I'm

00:23:33.180 --> 00:23:37.950
sure you know about
India as much as I know.

00:23:37.950 --> 00:23:39.660
That in India,
there are two things

00:23:39.660 --> 00:23:46.590
which are the most popular, I
would say, subjects in India.

00:23:46.590 --> 00:23:49.800
One is Bollywood, and
the other is cricket.

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:52.890
I mean, there's nothing which
is as popular as these two

00:23:52.890 --> 00:23:54.640
things in India.

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:58.050
So when you talk about
music, India always

00:23:58.050 --> 00:24:00.510
was dominated by
Bollywood music.

00:24:00.510 --> 00:24:03.350
And not for now, but always.

00:24:03.350 --> 00:24:04.980
SPEAKER: Always, yeah.

00:24:04.980 --> 00:24:06.630
PANKAJ UDHAS:
YouTube, fortunately,

00:24:06.630 --> 00:24:12.900
has opened up a new avenue for a
whole lot of singers who cannot

00:24:12.900 --> 00:24:15.930
make it big in Bollywood,
who may not make it big

00:24:15.930 --> 00:24:20.850
in Bollywood, or who probably
do not have the means,

00:24:20.850 --> 00:24:25.230
or maybe they do not have
an access to Bollywood.

00:24:25.230 --> 00:24:27.960
For all those singers, I
think its a great platform.

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:31.980
If they have the talent, it
will get recognized right away.

00:24:31.980 --> 00:24:34.830
And there couldn't
be anything which

00:24:34.830 --> 00:24:38.130
could be more rewarding than
YouTube, because you know it

00:24:38.130 --> 00:24:40.140
instantly.

00:24:40.140 --> 00:24:43.710
If your song is
popular on YouTube,

00:24:43.710 --> 00:24:46.190
you'll know by the
number of hits.

00:24:46.190 --> 00:24:49.440
You know by the number
of views, how many views,

00:24:49.440 --> 00:24:54.880
and you'll immediately know that
your song is liked by people.

00:24:54.880 --> 00:24:56.760
So I think it's
a great platform.

00:24:56.760 --> 00:24:57.957
It's a wonderful platform.

00:24:57.957 --> 00:24:58.540
SPEAKER: Good.

00:24:58.540 --> 00:24:59.890
Very nice.

00:24:59.890 --> 00:25:02.040
Another question I
wanted to ask you

00:25:02.040 --> 00:25:03.930
was about the creative process.

00:25:03.930 --> 00:25:06.720
Because people who do
playback boxing in Bollywood,

00:25:06.720 --> 00:25:08.700
do you go there, somebody
has done the lyrics,

00:25:08.700 --> 00:25:11.920
somebody has done the music,
you just go memorize your part.

00:25:11.920 --> 00:25:15.570
But ghazal singing and
producing an album, what you do,

00:25:15.570 --> 00:25:16.470
figuring out--

00:25:16.470 --> 00:25:19.440
share with us something about
that whole creative process.

00:25:19.440 --> 00:25:21.120
How do you come up
with the project?

00:25:21.120 --> 00:25:22.680
How do you select songs for it?

00:25:22.680 --> 00:25:24.630
What is that?

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:27.430
PANKAJ UDHAS: When I
started, I remember

00:25:27.430 --> 00:25:30.730
my early years of music.

00:25:30.730 --> 00:25:33.490
When you introduced me,
you talked about albums

00:25:33.490 --> 00:25:37.120
like "Aahat" and "Mukarrar."

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:41.530
During that period, I
remember that I had an option.

00:25:41.530 --> 00:25:43.330
I had a very dear friend.

00:25:43.330 --> 00:25:45.130
Unfortunately, he's no more.

00:25:45.130 --> 00:25:48.105
He was a poet.

00:25:48.105 --> 00:25:52.880
[INAUDIBLE] was his name,
and he was a brilliant poet.

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:57.900
He was kind of a
guide, kind of someone

00:25:57.900 --> 00:26:05.550
who guided me regularly as far
as Urdu poetry is concerned.

00:26:05.550 --> 00:26:08.210
So we were sitting
one day, and we

00:26:08.210 --> 00:26:16.940
were discussing as to how
the Urdu poetry, the content

00:26:16.940 --> 00:26:24.710
is relevant to this
generation of listeners.

00:26:24.710 --> 00:26:27.050
And we came to a
conclusion then poets

00:26:27.050 --> 00:26:31.610
like [INAUDIBLE],, all
brilliant poets, Ustad poets,

00:26:31.610 --> 00:26:33.180
as we call them.

00:26:33.180 --> 00:26:37.760
But in terms of
for the audiences,

00:26:37.760 --> 00:26:43.520
people had limited
access to that Urdu,

00:26:43.520 --> 00:26:47.390
which was written somewhere
in the 17th, 18th century.

00:26:47.390 --> 00:26:52.830
So we kind of took a
conscious decision that,

00:26:52.830 --> 00:26:58.140
why not approach the
poetry in a different way,

00:26:58.140 --> 00:27:00.960
so that we can
reach out to larger

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:03.360
audiences across the world.

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:09.150
And the first ghazal we
came across, which qualified

00:27:09.150 --> 00:27:15.420
or which suited our purposes,
was Jim [INAUDIBLE]..

00:27:15.420 --> 00:27:18.490
Because the poet
was written-- this

00:27:18.490 --> 00:27:26.700
was [INAUDIBLE] late
18th century poet.

00:27:26.700 --> 00:27:31.590
But he wrote it so simply
that [NON-ENGLISH]..

00:27:34.260 --> 00:27:40.070
So very simple to understand,
but wonderful meaning.

00:27:40.070 --> 00:27:43.910
Because, as you know, that
in Urdu, when you do it

00:27:43.910 --> 00:27:48.930
talk about a couplet, it has
about 20 different layers

00:27:48.930 --> 00:27:49.940
of meaning.

00:27:49.940 --> 00:27:51.950
It's not just one meaning.

00:27:51.950 --> 00:27:55.580
You can uncover so many layers.

00:27:55.580 --> 00:28:01.580
And when we tried to
figure out [NON-ENGLISH],,

00:28:01.580 --> 00:28:05.360
when you do a
literal translation,

00:28:05.360 --> 00:28:07.940
it means that you are talking
with some beautiful person who

00:28:07.940 --> 00:28:11.990
is very close to you, and you
are so very fortunate to have

00:28:11.990 --> 00:28:13.310
that person.

00:28:13.310 --> 00:28:15.980
Then if you open
up layers, then you

00:28:15.980 --> 00:28:21.580
realize that the poets, most
of the poets, they was Sufi,

00:28:21.580 --> 00:28:26.790
and they had such a major
spiritual approach in life.

00:28:26.790 --> 00:28:33.300
So actually, what the poet was
trying to say is that it's God

00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:41.360
Almighty, the people who
have that superpower or that

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:46.270
spiritual leader close
to them, [NON-ENGLISH]..

00:28:53.840 --> 00:28:54.710
SPEAKER: Right.

00:28:54.710 --> 00:29:00.000
PANKAJ UDHAS: So that means
that poetry is unbelievable,

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:02.870
and it's so simple.

00:29:02.870 --> 00:29:06.050
But at the same time,
it's so very effective.

00:29:06.050 --> 00:29:07.745
So that's when we
started talking

00:29:07.745 --> 00:29:09.050
about the creative process.

00:29:09.050 --> 00:29:12.980
That's when I started
focusing on poetry, which

00:29:12.980 --> 00:29:18.960
would have less of difficult
Persian words, Arabic words,

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:20.900
more of Hindu.

00:29:20.900 --> 00:29:26.864
And that's how I got into this
particular creative process.

00:29:26.864 --> 00:29:28.280
SPEAKER: And I
think you're right.

00:29:28.280 --> 00:29:30.620
What you brought to
the ghazal industry

00:29:30.620 --> 00:29:32.660
was an ability to
others to enjoy,

00:29:32.660 --> 00:29:35.920
not just somebody who
understands Urdu at that level.

00:29:35.920 --> 00:29:38.170
